Proceedings of the 2023 Conference on Empirical Methods in Natural Language Processing , pages 7101–7125
December 6-10, 2023 ©2023 Association for Computational Linguistics
Prompt-Based Monte-Carlo Tree Search for
Goal-oriented Dialogue Policy Planning
Xiao Yu, Maximillian Chen, Zhou Yu
Department of Computer Science, Columbia University, New York, NY
{xy2437, zy2461}@columbia.edu ,maxchen@cs.columbia.edu
Abstract
Planning for goal-oriented dialogue often re-
quires simulating future dialogue interactions
and estimating task progress. Many approaches
thus consider training neural networks to per-
form look-ahead search algorithms such as A*
search and Monte Carlo Tree Search (MCTS).
However, this training often requires abundant
annotated data, which creates challenges when
faced with noisy annotations or low-resource
settings. We introduce GDP-Z ERO, an ap-
proach using Open-Loop MCTS to perform
goal-oriented dialogue policy planning with-
out any model training .GDP-Z ERO prompts
a large language model to act as a policy

# Try to extract more text, especially the section describing the PUCT formula and MCTS details
import PyPDF2

with open('/workspace/benchmark/datasets/9-GDPZero/GDPZero/paper.pdf', 'rb') as f:
    reader = PyPDF2.PdfReader(f)
    text = ''
    for page in reader.pages:
        text += page.extract_text() + '\n'

# Try to find the PUCT formula or MCTS section
import re

# Look for PUCT, UCT, or MCTS formula
matches = re.findall(r'(PUCT|UCT|MCTS)[\s\S]{0,500}', text, re.IGNORECASE)

# Print a chunk of text around the first match
if matches:
    idx = text.lower().find(matches[0][0].lower())
    print(text[max(0, idx-500):idx+1000])
else:
    print(text[:4000])
